.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="6" pageNumber="83">
The genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Melidia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Melidia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Melidia</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Stål">Stal</normalizedToken>
, 1876 is characterized by the fastigium of the vertex, which is prominently raised in the region of the lateral ocelli. It looks like the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Phaneroptera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phaneroptera" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phaneroptera</taxonomicName>
, but differs from this mainly in the shape of the head, the male cerci and the sub-genital plate, and broader fore wings. It has a well-developed spine on the fore coxae and males have the stridulatory region of the left tegmina brown or conspicuously marked with brown (
<bibRefCitation author="Ragge, DR" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin British Museum (Natural History) Entomology" pageId="14" pageNumber="91" pagination="1 - 192" title="A review of the African Phaneropterinae with open tympana (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae)." url="http://www.archive.org/details/bulletinofbritis40entolond" volume="40" year="1980">Ragge 1980</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
